ON NOVEMBER 9, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, SERIAL NUMBER GATX 42159, LOADED WITH CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' LATANIER, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE TANK CAR LEAKED ONLY WHILE IN MOTION, THEREFORE THE CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE.  THE SPILLAGE FROM A DEFECTIVE RUPTURE DISK WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP PORTION OF THE TANK AND NO MATERIAL CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE GROUND.THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED MR. AUDIE RICHARD, WITH UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES,  OUT OF BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA TO REPAIR A DEFECTIVE DISK AND DECON THE TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS REPAIRED AND RELEASED FOR DESTINATION ON NOVEMBER 10, 1997 AT 0900 HOURS.

ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, UTLX 75761, NOVEMBER 4, 1997, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 HOURS, TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 4, 1997, AT CARNEYS POINT YARD IN DEEPWATER, NJ, WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, AN FRA INSPECTOR NOTED COMMODITY ON SIDE OF TANK CAR UTLX 75761 CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID, N.O.S. (WASTE WATER WITH TRACE OF SOLVENT). AN INBOUND CAR INSPECTOR FROM DUPONT, THE CONSIGNEE, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED IT HAD ONE (1) OF EIGHT (8) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. NO REPORT OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY DUPONT'S INBOUND CAR INSPECTOR WHO TIGHTENED ONE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT THAT REQUIRED 5-6 FULL TURNS. TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO CONSIGNEE.

DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT A CUSTOMER LOCATION, TANK LOAD OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, 50% LIQUID. DRIVER COULD NOT PRESSURIZE VESSEL AND WAS RETURNING TO MTR FACILITY FOR REPAIRS. DURING RETURN TRIP THE VACUUM VENT LOCATED IN THE DOME LID CAME LOOSE (ATTACHING LOCK RING FAILED) AND THE VENT FELL INTO THE TANK. THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT OF THE VENT HOLE IN THE DOME LID AND ACCUMULATE IN THE CATCH AREA ON TOP OF THE TANKER. WHEN THE VEHICLE MOVED THE PRODUCT IN THE DOME CATCH AREA MOVED INTO THE DRAIN HOLES AND DRIPPED OUT THE DRAIN TUBES. THIS PRODUCT DRIPPED ON THE ROADWAY OVER A H BLOCK SECTION. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS, IMMEDIATE REPLACE VENT. FUTURE - INCLUDE A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THIS VENT WHEN FILLING VESSEL. ALSO CHECKED ALL OTHER TANKERS WITH THIS SAME DESIGN OF VACUUM VENT. THE PRODUCT WHICH DRIPPED FROM DRAIN LINES WAS UNRECOVERABLE.

YARD SWITCH CREW REPORTED STENCH WHILE WORKING NEAR TANK CAR PLMX 9206, A RESIDUE SHIPMENT OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE CAR AND FOUND VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. AS A PRECAUTION, THE CAR WAS TAKEN TO BECKER FOR ISOLATION AND REPAIRS. ON 11/12, REPAIRS WERE COMPLETE. TWO 'O' RINGS REQUIRED REPLACEMENT ACCOUNT DETERIORATED. AFTER OBSERVATION, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION. INBOUND TRAIN"M-DEMBELI-10A

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DURING OUTBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, CAR INSPECTORS REPORTED STENCH OF A PRODUCT NEAR TANK CAR TRLX 33512, A RESIDUE SHIPMENT OF GASOLINE. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE 2" VALVE PLUG LOOSELY IN PLACE. THE VALVE WAS FULLY CLOSED AND THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED TO STOP THE RELEASE. ALL PRODUCT EVAPORATED QUICKLY FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. INBOUND TRAIN: M-BAKBAR3-13A

WHILE AWAITING MECHANICAL REPAIRS, TANK CAR PROX 41126, A LOAD OF ACETIC ANHYDRIDE, WAS FOUND TO BE DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. A BUCKET WAS PLACED TO CATCH THE DRIPS AND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO THE CONTAINMENT PIT TRACK. BNSF RESPONDERS ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS THAT SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY TO THE FLANGE PLATE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. ALL ATTEMPTS WERE UNSUCCESSFUL DUE TO AN APPARENT FAILED GASKET. THE SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM SUPERVISED THE TRANSFER TO ANOTHER TANK CAR (WHICH WAS PERFORMED BY A CONTRACTOR). THE CAR WAS ROUTED TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND REPAIR. INBOUND TRAIN: V-SDGKCKI-IIA

THE TRACTOR TRAILER RIG WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON  I-65 WHEN A MECHANICAL FAILURE IN THE TRACTOR CREATED A FIRE.  THE RIG WAS PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND THE DRIVER EXITED THE CAB.  THE FIRE CONTINUED TO BURN AND SPREAD TO THE TRAILER.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT, CONDUCTED TRAFFIC CONTROL OPERATIONS, AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. HAZMAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVE ONSITE, CONDUCTED AIR MONITORING AND INSPECTED THE TRAILER.  TWO PALLETS OF PRODUCT WERE DAMAGED, RELEASING APPROX. 4,000 POUNDS ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ASPHALT SURFACE.  THE OTHER PALLETS REMAINED UNDAMAGED.  THE UNDAMAGED PALLETS WERE TRANSFERRED TO A SECOND TRAILER.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN DRUMS. THE DRUMS WERE LOADED ONTO THE SECOND TRAILER AND RELEASE FROM THE SITE.  THE AREA WAS WASHED TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT.

column168: DRIVER TEAM ENROUTE AND STOPPED AT THIS SCALE DUE TO AN ODOR OF THE PRODUCT WHEN THEY GOT OUT TO CHECK TIRES. column168: THE SHIPPER PERSONNEL HOOKED A HOSE TO THE STORAGE TANK CONNECTION AND TOLD DRIVER TO GO BACK OUTSIDE TO THE TANK TRAILER AND START THE UNLOAD PROCESS. DRIVER HEARD RUMBLING SOUND AND RE-ENTERED THE BUILDING IN TIME TO SEE THE ATTENDANT STANDING ON A WALKWAY ABOVE THE STORAGE TANK AND THEN AN EXPLOSION OCCURRED, SPEWING THE CONTENTS OF THE STORAGE TANK UP THROUGH ITS DOME LID AND ONTO THE GIRDERS, CEILING AND FLOOR. THERE WAS A LOT OF SMOKE. WHEN THE SMOKE CLEARED, THE DRIVER RE-ENTERED THE BUILDING TO LOOK FOR THE ATTENDANT, WHO HAD MANAGED TO GET INTO AN OFFICE BEFORE THE ACTUAL EXPLOSION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. ALL MATERIALS WERE CONTAINED INSIDE THE PLANT BUILDING. THE CUSTOMER ATTENDANT HAD INTRODUCED THE PRODUCT INTO A TANK THAT ALREADY CONTAINED HYDROGEN PEROXIDE. THIS WAS AN INCOMPATIBLE MIXTURE.

WHILE UNLOADING A 1000 GALLON TANK OFF BED OF BOOM TRUCK, THE BOOM TRUCK TIPPED OVER ONTO ITS SIDE. A 1000 GALLON TANK ON THE BED OF THE TRUCK SLID OFF AND STRUCK THE GROUND. THE FLOAT GAUGE WAS JARRED LOOSE, A VAPOR RELEASE OCCURRED. APPROX 20 TO 25 GALLONS RELEASED. ONEONTA FIRE DEPT AND ALABAMA LP GAS BOARD INSPECTOR, GERALD SMITH WAS AT THE SCENE. POLICE DEPT SHUT DOWN 2ND AVE S.EVACUATION OF 4 TO 5 AREA RESIDENTS. VAPOR DISPERSED INTO ATMOSPHERE. I LEARNED OF THE EVACUATION AND SHUT DOWN OF 2ND AVE FROM FIRE CHIEF, CHARLES MONTGOMERY ON THE 25TH OF NOV. I IMMEDIATELY PHONED DOT. THE DAY THE INCIDENT OCCURRED I CONTATED THE AL DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MGMT. I SPOKE TO FRANK NORTH ON THAT DATE. NO INJURIES.

column168: A LOAD OF VARIOUS WASTES CAME IN TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY IN HEATH OH. AT THE FACILITY MARK PATTERSON NOTICED A STRONG ODOR OF GASOLINE EMITTING FROM THE TRAILER WHERE THE DRUMS WERE LOCATED. MARK HAD THE TRAILER PULLED AWAY FROM THE FACILITY BUILDING AND NOTICED SOME LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR. SAFETY KLEEN PERSONNEL FROM HEBRON OH, RESPONDED TO REMEDIATE THE INCIDENT. THE FOUND 1-55 GALLON DRUM OF GASOLINE HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM DUE TO RUST. CLEAN UP COST WAS APPROXIMATELY $700.00. THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS RECOVERED INTO 1-30 GALLON DRUM AND 1-55 GALLON DRUM AND THE LEAKY CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED. 12 PALLETS WERE ALSO CONTAMINATED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS WASTE.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 20, 1997, THE DRIVER PICKED UP A SEALED SLUDGE BOX (PORTABLE TANK) DESIGNED TO BE TRANSPORTED ON A ROLL OFF TRAILER AT JAGEMANN PLATING. WHEN THE MATERIAL WAS ORIGINALLY PLACED INTO THE ROLL OFF BOX ON NOVEMBER 17, 1997, IT WAS A FLOW ABLE SEMI SOLID SLUDGE. DURING THE TIME THAT THE BOX SAT ON SITE, THE MATERIAL SEPARATED AND THE SOLIDS SETTLED OUT. THE BOX WAS PICKED UP ON THE 20TH WITHOUT INCIDENT. AS THE DRIVER APPROACHED MILWAUKEE,  HE ENCOUNTERED HEAVIER RUSH HOUR TRAFFIC. BRAKING FOR TRAFFIC CAUSED A LIQUID SURGE WITHIN THE BOX. WHEN THE SURGE HIT THE REAR, REMOVABLE, BULKHEAD, IT CAUSED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO LEAK OUT OF THE SEAL BETWEEN THE CONTAINER AND THE BULKHEAD. THE DRIVER NOTICED THE MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM THE CONTAINER AND IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE DISPATCH OFFICE WAS CONTACTED AND A VACUUM TANKER WAS DISPATCHED TO PUMP OFF ENOUGH OF THE LIQUID TO FACILITATE MAKING THE REPAIRS. AFTER THE LIQUID WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE TANKER BOTH VEHICLES WERE TRANSPORTED TO OUR PORT WASHINGTON TSDF WHERE REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE CONTAINER. THE MATERIALS WERE COMBINED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DESTINATION FACILITY.

WHEN THE DRIVER STOPED TO MAKE HIS NEXT PICK UP, AFTER PICKING UP THE DRUMS FROM NAPCO INTERNATIONAL, HE NOTICED THAT SOME MATERIAL HAD SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY WHICH CONTAINER HAD LEAKED AND ATTEMPTED TO OVERPACK THE CONTAINER INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO OVERPACK THE CONTAINER IT SLIPPED AND FELL TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE IMPACT WITH THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER CAUSED THE LID TO POP OFF THE DRUM AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUMS RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS USING A TRAILER EQUIPPED WITH A SPILL PAN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM. APPARENTLY A SMALL HOLE EXISTED IN ONE OF THE WELDS OF THE SPILL PAN BECAUSE ABOUT ONE POUND OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO A PAVED SURFACE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED USING A CLAY ABSORBENT, AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR SHIPMENT TO THE TSDF DESIGNATED ON THE MANIFEST. THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WHICH SPILLED WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR TRANSPORT TO THE TSDF.
A SAFETY KLEEN REP WAS CARRYING A RENTAL PUMP OUT OF HIS FRS OUT TRUCK.  THAT PUMP WAS USED TO PUMP THE CUSTOMER'S OIL THAT WAS FOUND TO BE CONTAMINATED WITH 1,1,1, TRICHLOROETHANE.

THE LEAK WAS SPOTTED DURING A NORMAL CHECK WHILE AT THE DRIVER'S TRAVEL PLAZA TRUCK STOP AT SAN JON, NM.  THERE IS NO FACILITY IN SAN JON TO HANDLE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SO THE TUCUMCARI, NM FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRANGED FOR A COMPANY TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP.  THE CLEANUP COMPANY CONTAINED THE SPILL, PUT THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE RESIDUE FROM THE CLEANUP INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SHIPPED THE DRUM BACK TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER.

A 30 GALLON DRUM OF PETROLEUM NAPTHA FELL OFF OF THE BACK OF A SAFETY KLEEN TRUCK WHILE BEING LOADED. THE DRUM FELL ONTO THE GROUND (GRAVEL) BELOW AND THE LID POPPED OFF. DURING THE PROCESS THEY USED A PID DETECTOR TO MONITOR THE AREA AND TOOK TWO SAMPLES FROM THE HOLE AND SENT THEM OFF FOR ANALYSIS. THE SAFETY KLEEN CUSTOMER WAS SATISFIED WITH THE RECOVERY.

A SYNCOR VEHICLE WAS DELIVERING CONTAINERS TO SEVERAL HOSPITALS. THE CONTAINERS ARE USED TO DELIVER UNIT DOSES OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL USED IN MEDICAL IMAGING. THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON INTERSTATE 20 WHEN HE TRAVELED OVER A SECTION OF HIGHWAY COVERED WITH STANDING WATER. THE VEHICLE HYDROPLANED ACROSS THE WATER STRIKING A TREE. A LOCAL FIRE AND RESCUE UNIT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT. THE PHARMACY MANAGER AND A  SECOND PHARMACIST RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO HELP PERFORM SURVEYS OF THE AREA. THE STATE RADIATION AGENCY ALSO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO HELP PERFORM SURVEYS OF THE AREA. THE STATE RADIATION AGENCY ALSO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE AREA WAS SECURED FOR OVER ONE HOUR TO ALLOW SURVEYS TO BE COMPLETED. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING FOUR CONTAINERS OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL. TWO CONTAINERS WERE LABELED RADIOACTIVE WHITE I AND TWO CONTAINERS WERE LABELED RADIOACTIVE YELLOW II. THREE OF THE FOUR CONTAINERS WERE EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE. THE CONTAINERS DID NOT OPEN ON IMPACT. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED DURING THE ACCIDENT.

column168: THE DRUMS IN QUESTION WERE PLACED ON PALLETS AND SHRINK WRAPPED. THEY WERE LOADED ON A BOX TRAILER IN SYRACUSE, NY TO BE TAKEN TO THE FINAL DISPOSAL FACILITY. AT THE NEXT STOP IN ALBANY NY, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT 3 OF THE 20 PAILS HAD SPILLED SOME OF THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID. LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF ACID SPILLED AND IT REMAINED ON THE TRAILER. THE SPILLED ACID WAS IMMEDIATELY NEUTRALIZED, CLEANED UP AND THEN PLACED IN A METAL DRUM. THE PPE USED DURING THE CLEANUP WAS ALSO PLACED IN A DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE REMAINING 17 PAILS AND DRUM CONTAINING THE 3 PAILS WERE RECEIVED AT THE FINAL DISPOSAL FACILITY AS SCHEDULED. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WE WILL REMIND BOTH OUR CUSTOMERS AND DRIVERS OF THEIR RESPONSIBILITIES FOR PROPER PACKAGING AND TRANSPORT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, WHICH INCLUDES HAZARDOUS WASTE. OUR DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO VISUALLY INSPECT THE CLOSURE DEVICES OF CONTAINERS TO VERIFY SECUREMENT AND CLOSURE.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DIESEL FUEL FROM CARGO TANK TO STORAGE TANK. HE HAD HOOKED UP ALL HOSES AND STARTED PUMPING.  HE HAD WENT AROUND THE TRUCK TO GET THE THROTTLE AT 800 RPM.  WHEN HE WENT BACK HE SAW THAT THE HOSE HAD CAME OFF THE PUMP AND THERE WAS DIESEL SPRAYING. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN PUMPING.  APPARENTLY VIBRATION FROM PUMP CAUSED THE EARS TO COME LOOSE.  THE EARS ON HOSES ARE SUPPOSE TO BE TIED DOW TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING BUT DRIVER HAD NOT BEEN FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURES. THE CAMLOCK FITTING ON CUSTOMER HOSE WAS WORN AND GASKET WAS ALSO BAD.

IT HAD ALREADY BEEN CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND WERE RETURNED IT TO THE SHIPPER. THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO THE CUSTOMER TANK, AND AS THE PRODUCT EMPTIED OUT THE HOSE STARTED JUMPING UP AND DOWN, AND THE AIR PRESSURE GAGE ON OUR TANK SHOWED TO DROP. THE DRIVER THEN BLOCKED IN THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES ON OUR TANK, THEN SHUT THE CUSTOMER VALVE. HE THEN LOOSENED ONE EAR ON THE HOSE TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE AND MOVED THE HOSE IN A SIDE TO SIDE MOTION, AND DID NOT HEAR OR SEE ANY AIR, OR ACID. HE THEN LOOSENED THE OTHER EAR ON THE HOSE, AND THATS WHEN THE VAPOR SPRAY BLEW UP HIS SLEEVE AND HIS WRIST WERE BURNT FROM THE ACID SPRAY. WE NOW HAVE A BLOW DOWN VALVE WHICH WILL ASSIST THE DRIVER IN RELIEVING THE PRESSURE FROM HIS TANK WITHOUT HAVING TO UNLATCH HIS EARS ON THE HOSE.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS STRUCK BY OTHER FREIGHT ON THE BELT IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  IT APPEARED TO BE DAMAGED AND THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED.  DURING SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES THE CONTENTS WERE INSPECTED.  THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED AEROSOL CANS. THE PACKAGE WAS NO PACKAGED, MARKED LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DANAGEROUS GOODS.  THE SHIPMENT IS THUS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY "AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, NOS".  I DO NOT HAVE A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ON THIS SHIPMENT. IT'S POSSIBLE THAT IT WOULD MEET THE DEFINITION OF FLAMMABLE GAS UNDER IATA.  THERE IS AN INDICATION ON THE AEROSOL CANS THAT THEY ARE HIGHLY FLAMMABLE.  I REPORTED THIS SHIPMENT TO FAA AGENT LYNN LEONARD AT 404-305-7185.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

WHILE ON CALL, I WAS BEEPED TO CALL OUR GLOBAL OPERATIONS CONTROL (GOC) AT 2242 PM CENTRAL TIME.  AT THAT TIME, GOC EMPLOYEE TOM WATKINS REPORTED TO ME THAT FEDEX FLIGHT #1292 WHICH ORIGINATED IN ROCHESTER, NY WHICH WAS DESTINED FOR MEMPHIS, TN HAD DIVERTED TO INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA DUE TO AN ODOR BEING DETECTED BY CREW MEMBERS ON THE AIRCRAFT DURING THE FLIGHT.  AT THAT TIME I PHONED OUR ROCHESTER, NY RAMP AND SPOKE WITH DG AGENT, GREG WHEAT.  HE INDICATED THAT THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1000LBS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID ON THE AIRCRAFT AND I ASKED HIM TO FAX THE PART A PAPERWORK TO THE INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA HUB.  AFTER THE CREW MEMBERS LANDED ON OXYGEN THEY DOWNLOADED THE HAZ CAN.  I SPOKE WITH DG AGENT BOB CRAWFORD WHO SAID THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A SHIPMENT OF FOUR DRUMS OF "FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS", UN 1993 FROM ONE SHIPPER.  BOB CRAWFORD INDICATED TO ME THAT THERE APPEARED TO BE NO LOADING ERRORS MADE AT OUR ROCHESTER RAMP.  THE DRUMS WERE LOADED CORRECTLY, SECURED UNDER THE HAZ NETS, THE HOSE WAS CONNECTED, THE DRUMS WERE LOADED UPRIGHT, THE CARGO DOORS WERE SECURELY IN PLACE. I PHONED THE ROCHESTER RAMP TO COMMUNICATE THIS TO GREG WHEAT.  I'M TOLD THE CREW MEMBERS DID LAND ON OXYGEN.  THE PLANE DID DEPART FROM INDIANAPOLIS AFTER THE HAZ CAN WITH THE ODOROUS FREIGHT HAD BEEN REMOVED.  THE NEXT DAY, THE ODOR FROM THE PACKAGES HAD DISSIPATED.  AS THERE WERE NO PACKAGE DISCREPANCIES WITH THE SHIPMENT, IT WAS TRUCKED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED THE NIGHT OF THE DIVERSION BY LOCAL PERSONNEL IN INDIANAPOLIS.  THE AIRBILL NUMBER WAS 02377873143.  THE AIRCRAFT TAIL NUMBER WAS 104FE.

column168: VII & VIII ABOVE NO PACKAGING FAILURE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING GASOLINE INTO A MC-306 CARGO TANK FOR DELIVERY TO A CONVENIENCE STORE. HE HAD COMPLETED LOADING ONE COMPARTMENT AND HAD RESET THE METER TO LOAD THE SECOND COMPARTMENT. FOR UNKNOWN REASONS, HE FORGOT TO SWITCH THE LOADING ARM ONTO THE SECOND COMPARTMENT. WHEN HE ACTIVATED THE PUMP, GAS WAS PUT INTO A LOADED COMPARTMENT. ABOUT 50 GALLONS OF GAS WAS FORCED INTO THE TRAILER'S VAPOR RECOVERY LINES BEFORE THE OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM WAS ABLE TO SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THE GAS IN THE VAPOR LINES WAS DRAINED INTO A HOLDING TANK AT THE TERMINAL WHERE IT WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED REFERENCE NUMBER 97-09842 TO THIS INCIDENT. NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER MIKE SEABAUGH AND THEN CONTACTED CONTRACTOR, HULCHER SERVICES TO RESPOND AND MITIGATE. MR TIM COX DIRECTOR HAZ MAT HULCHER SERVICES RESPONDED FROM HIGHLAND IL AND DETERMINED THAT SAMPLE VALVE WAS LOOSE ALLOWING MINIMAL LESS THAN ONE GALLON PRODUCT TO ESCAPE CONTAINER. MR COX WAS SUCCESSFUL IN REPAIRING THE VALVE BY TIGHTENING IT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, SPARKS NV., WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS UNION PACIFIC SPARKS YARD NOTED PATTERN DAMPNESS ORIGINATING FROM UNDERNEATH HINGED COMBINATION HOUSING COVER DOWN SIDE OF TANK CAR ADMX30269. DENATURED ALCOHOL. REMOVED INTAT SEAL ADM-CR BV 7334 OPENED COVER NOTED LEAKAGE FROM AROUND THREADS WHERE LIQUID BALL VALVE THREADS ONTO LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE. LEAKAGE WAS ALSO NOTED WHERE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE THREADED INTO BLIND FLANGE ASSEMBLY UNDERNEATH COMBINATION HOUSING COVER. LOOSE FITTINGS WERE TIGHTENED AFTER INTERNAL PRESSURE IN CAR WAS RELIEVED. TANK CAR WAS REINSPECTED ON TWO FOLLOW UP INSPECTIONS WITH NO EXCEPTI0NS. SEAL UPF 329855 WAS APPLIED FOR PROTECTION. TRACY JACKSON, CHEMTREC WAS FURNISHED DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT #62193.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY CHEYENNE YARD MASTER, THAT FIVE CARS WERE DERAILED FROM A SWITCH MOVE, DERAILED CARS WERE LOCATED AT WEST END OF YARDS, SOUTH 7 TRACK. INCLUDED WITHIN THE DERAILMENT WAS NATX 29724, WHICH WAS ON ITS SIDE WITH MANWAY FACING NORTH. MANWAY WAS LEAKING ABOUT ONE QUART PER MINUTE. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THREE OUT OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, WHICH ALLOWED MANWAY GASKET TO BLOW OUT SIDE OF MANWAY DURING DERAILMENT. TIGHTEN MANWAY SWING BOLTS AND USED VARIOUS PRODUCTS TO LESSEN LEAK TO ABOUT ONE PINT PER MINUTE. CHEYENNE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND USAF FOAM UNIT WERE AT THE SCENE AND PLACED A CATCH BASIN UNDER THE MANWAY. ABOUT 1000 GALLONS HAD ALREADY POOLED UNDER DERAILED CARS.CONTRACTORS MUNCHIANDO AND Z & S WERE SUMMONED TO THE SCENE. CONTACTED SID WHITE AND SHIPPER AND WAS ADVISED WE COULD UNLOAD TRANSFERRED PRODUCT AT COASTAL CHEM, FIVE MILES WEST OF DERAILMENT SITE. ABOUT 27210 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS AND UNLOADED AT COASTAL AND Z & S. TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT 1335, 11/8/97. BOB WIBLE CHEMTREC REPORT # 62187, AND MARK IBSEN , SAND CREEK CHEMICAL WERE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT. ALSO RMCC WAS UPDATED THROUGHOUT THE ENTIRE INCIDENT.

INSPECTION ON TOP OF TANK FOUND BOLTS LOOSE AND LYING IN SPILL BOX FROM BLIND FLANGE ASSEMBLY LOCATED ON LIQUID/ VAPOR EDUCTION PIPE. THIS ASSEMBLY WAS EQUIPPED WITH A BALL VALVE THAT WAS NOTED IN THE CLOSED POSITION. BOLTS/ NUTS WERE SECURED ON ASSEMBLY. CHEMTREC BOB WIBLE WAS FURNISHED DETAILS AND ASSIGNED #62329.

column168: IMPROPER PACKAGING, SOO 63561, NOVEMBER 8, 1997, ALBANY DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1520 HOURS, SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 8, 1997, CONRAIL'S ALBANY MOVEMENT DESK WAS NOTIFIED BY THE D & H RAILROAD YARDMASTER AT BUFFALO, NEW YORK THAT GONDOLA SOO 63531, IN D & H TRAIN HAD BEEN DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE ON THE CONRAIL HOWARD STREET RUNNER TRACK.  THE GONDOLA HAD BEEN DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING A PREARRANGED INSPECTION OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARS IN THE TRAIN BY US DOT FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTOR AND A CP FIELD MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, SOO 73561 WAS TRAVELING UNDER DOT EXEMPTION 11991. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1820 HOURS, ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, A CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND UPON EXAMINING THE CAR, THEY DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS IMPROPERLY PACKAGED.  ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TOPPED THE LEAKING GONDOLA BY APPLYING A CONTAINMENT PATCH.  ONCE CONTAINED, THE TRAIN MOVED INTO THE D&H YARD AT APPROXIMATELY 2220 HOURS.  CONTAINER IS26268 WAS FOUND LEAKING AT AN OLD DAMAGED AREA AT THE UNLOADING GATE.  CONTAINER 12658 WAS IN THE SAME GONDOLA AND WAS FOUND NOT BE LEAKING.  ON NOVEMBER 13, 1997, BOTH CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE GONDOLA AND EPOXY PUTT PATCH WAS APPLIED TO THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THE CONTAMINATED LINER WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW LINER AND THE TWO CONTAINERS WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE SAME GONDOLA CAR AND OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT APPROXIMATELY 2100 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 14, 1997.  PLEASE NOTE:  DURING THE INSPECTION, THE CP FIELD MANAGER, HAZ MAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE, E J STEENHORST CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LEAKING PRODUCT. MR. STEENHORST TOOK HIMSELF TO BUFFALO GENERAL HOSPITAL AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FOR EXPOSURE TO THE CHEMICAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE CARGO TANK TRUCK DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-81 ENROUTE BACK TO THE PLANT TO RELOAD. THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING IN RAIN BEHIND THREE (3) OTHER VEHICLES. THE THIRD VEHICLE IN FRONT, ABRUPTLY APPLIED BRAKES TO EXIT AT AN OFF RAMP WHICH CAUSED A CHAIN REACTION. OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE WHEN HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES, SLIDING BACKWARDS INTO THE MEDIAN AND OVERTURNED ONTO PASSENGER SIDE OF TRUCK. ANOTHER CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO CAUSE OF ACCIDENT, BESIDES THE RAIN, MAY HAVE BEEN FROM THE RESULT OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED ON THE HIGHWAY SURFACE FROM A PREVIOUS ACCIDENT. THE PREVIOUS ACCIDENT HAD JUST BEEN REMOVED MOMENTS BEFORE AND APPROXIMATELY EIGHTY YARDS PRIOR TO THIS ACCIDENT. THE OVERTURN IMPACT CAUSED BREAKAGE OF REAR DECK 2" PLUMBING AT A BACK CHECK VALVE INTO THE CARGO TANK. THE CONTENTS OF THE PLUMBING METER AND PUMP EXHAUSTED TO THE ATMOSPHERE IMMEDIATELY. THE BACK CHECK VALVE CONTAINED REMAINING PRODUCT (APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS) IN CARGO TANK; BUT ALLOWED MINIMAL LEAKAGE. WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF THE JOHNSON CITY, TN FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZ MAT TEAM THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS SAFELY DISPERSED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. TELEPHONE REPORT TO DOT: 11/14/97 @ 1653 HRS; CASE # 411626; MR. ALLEN RUTHERFORD.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 7, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:23 PM CDT, MR. STEPHEN TIDD, OF CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, L.C. (CES), WAS NOTIFIED OF A METHYLENE CHLORIDE RELEASE AT THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE BY MR. JEFF COONEY OF TRI STATE MOTOR TRANSIT COMPANY. THE RELEASE OCCURRED ON NOVEMBER 7, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 P.M. CDT, WHEN TRACTOR TRAILER RIG, OPERATED BY A REPRESENTATIVE OF TRI STATE MOTOR TRANSIT COMPANY, NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER AFTER HE HAD STOPPED AT THE REST AREA. TWO DRUMS WERE DAMAGED DURING LOADING OPERATIONS OR HAD RUBBED AGAINST AN OBJECT INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE TWO DRUMS BEGAN TO LEAK WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ASPHALT SURFACE AT THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION. DUE TO THE PRESENCE OF A STRONG BLEACH SMELL AND UNKNOWN IDENTITY OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER ADVISED THAT THE DRIVER NOT MAKE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER TO IDENTIFY THE DAMAGED DRUMS AND TO LEAVE THE TRAILER DOORS CLOSED UNTIL RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE. THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER NOTIFIED OUR LOCAL CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE THE EXTENT OF IMPACT ASSOCIATED WITH THE RELEASE. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE PERSONNEL ASSESSED THE SITE CONDITIONS AND CONTACTED MR. TIDD TO DISCUSS CLEAN-UP OPTIONS. CONCERN ABOUT THE RELEASE OCCURRING IN A PUBLIC REST AREA, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE INCIDENT BY THE RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO ESTABLISH A SAFETY PERIMETER AROUND THE TRAILER. THE AMBIENT AIR INSIDE THE TRAILER WAS CHECKED FOR LEL, OXYGEN LEVELS, AND TOXIC GAS TO DETERMINE THE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, RESPONSE PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND IDENTIFIED THE TWO DAMAGED DRUMS OF METHYLENE CHLORIDE. THE TWO DRUMS WERE PLUGGED TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT AND PLACED INTO TWO 95-GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS. THE UNDAMAGED CARGO IN THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO AN UNAFFECTED AREA INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO THE AFFECTED AREAS OF THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE SPENT ABSORBENT WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO ONE 55-GALLON DRUM. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO THE SMALL AREA OF AFFECTED ASPHALT AND WORKED IN WITH BROOMS. THE SPENT ABSORBENT WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO THE 55-GALLON DRUM CONTAINING THE SPENT ABSORBENT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE TWO OVERPACK DRUMS AND ONE 55-GALLON DRUM WERE LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER AND THE TRACTOR-TRAILER RIG WAS RELEASED FROM THE SITE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS PART OF THE INBOUND PACKAGE LOAD INTO SAN ANTONIO ON 11/08.  THE ROOT OF THE PROBLEM CENTERED AROUND THE FACT THAT A PICK UP CYCLE COURIER (ROBERT LYONS) HAD SOMEHOW INADVERTENTLY FAILED TO SECURE THE READ DOT OF HIS VEHICLE.  THIS RESULTED IN THE DOOR OF THE VEHICLE COMING OPEN AND THE LOSS OF SEVERAL PACKAGES INTO TRAFFIC. TWO OF THE PACKAGES LOST WERE LATER DETERMINED TO BE DIAGNOSTIC SHIPMENTS OF CHIMPS BLOOD BEING SHIPPED ON DRY ICE TO THE SOUTHWEST FOUNDATION FOR TESTING.  SOME PEDESTRIANS IN THE SAN ANTONIO AREA OBSERVED THE PACKAGE FALL OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND REPORTED IT TO FEDEX AND PUBLIC HEALTH OFFICIALS IN THE SNA ANTONIO AREA.  A SEARCH WAS INITIATED FOR THE MISSING PIECES.  THE SEARCH LATER THAT AFTERNOON PRODUCED THE REMNANTS OF THE MISSING PACKAGES WHICH HAD BEEN SEVERELY DAMAGED BY THE TRAFFIC.  THE VIALS, SWABS AND PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH THE DAMAGED PIECES WERE RECOVERED AND TURNED OVER TO LABORATORY OFFICIALS.  THE BLOOD WAS BEING TESTED FOR THE PRESENCE OF THE VIRUS HERPES SIMPLEX-B.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE PACKAGE TO THAT EFFECT BUT THE SHIPMENT DID EXHIBIT THE MARKINGS AND LABELS FOR DRY ICE.  THE FAA AND CDC WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENTS.

FIRST STRIKE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. JIM ROLES WAS THE FIRST STRIKE EMPLOYEE THAT SUPERVISED THE CLEAN UP EFFORT. ACCORDING TO MR.
